article.headline: San Diego State 66, San Diego 63
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A freshman's poise and a coach's meltdown in a one-point game helped determine San Diego's crosstown rivalry. Freshman Brandon Heath scored 27 points, including the last five of the game, and San Diego State held off a wild rally by San Diego for a 66-63 victory Wednesday night. San Diego coach Brad Holland was whistled for a technical foul with 31.2 seconds left and SDSU leading 64-63. Holland yelled at referee Dave Libby that Brice Vounang got fouled when his shot was blocked by Aerick Sanders seconds earlier. Heath calmly made both free throws for a 66-63 lead, and neither team scored again. Holland was still irate after the game. "You make your own determination on that technical," Holland told reporters afterward. "At that point in the game, you tell me what was up with that. I didn't swear at him, I didn't do anything. All I said was, `Dave, that was a foul.' " The Aztecs (4-2) blew a 20-point lead in the second half before Heath bailed them out in the final minutes by scoring their last nine points. USD (1-5), which made it to the NCAA tournament last year, lost the crosstown rivalry for the second straight year. "We did everything right in the second half but win," Holland said. San Diego State led 49-29 with 16:55 left before USD went on a 31-10 run to take a 60-59 lead on a 3-pointer by Brad Lechtenberg with 2:49 to play. Heath gave SDSU the lead for good, 64-63, on a 3-pointer with 1:39 left. After Heath made the free throws following the technical, Lechtenberg missed a 3-pointer with 10 seconds left. He had made his first five 3s -- a career-high -- to help USD rally. "I'm used to the pressure. I played in a lot of big games in high school," said Heath, who went to Los Angeles' Westchester High. "I'm used to playing in front of big crowds. I'm very comfortable in that situation." Aztecs coach Steve Fisher said Heath "is unafraid. I like that about him. He comes from a high school program that is used to great success." Brice Vounang scored 21 for USD and Lechtenberg had 15. Tommy Johnson was the only other Aztec in double figures, with 10 points. San Diego State was 7-of-14 from the 3-point line in the first half in taking a 40-27 lead.
